rseman who guards crops’, or ‘mounted warrior, knight’. Compare   Knight  .","English: habitational name from Ryther, near Selby (Yorkshire), probably from Old English <i>ryther</i> ‘clearing’.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>ridere</i> ‘dweller at a clearing’ (see   Reeder  ) or ‘dweller by a small stream’, depending on which sense of Middle English <i>ride</i> the surname is derived from. These topographic senses of <i>Rider</i> are limited to the southern counties of England (especially Surrey, Sussex, and Hampshire), where topographic names in <i>-er</i> and the Middle English words <i>ride</i> ‘clearing’ and <i>rithe</i> ‘small stream’ are mainly found. See also   Reed  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":69,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":78,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705205,"age":89,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Thomas Ryder was born in 1480, in Yorkshire, England. He died on 9 April 1575, in Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England, at the age of 95."},"et":{"1480–9 April 1575":"1480–9. aprill 1575","1491–1535":"1491–1535","1480–1580":"1480–1580","1510–1542":"1510–1542","1510–Male":"1510–Surnud","1480–1575":"1480–1575","4 Jan 1535":"4. jaanuar 1535","2 October 1542":"2. oktoober 1542","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1575":"1575","1542":"1542","9 April 1575":"9. aprill 1575","about 1510":"umbes 1510","1549":"1549","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","Muckleton, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England"},"fi":{"1480–9 April 1575":"1480–9. huhtikuuta 1575","1491–1535":"1491–1535","1480–1580":"1480–1580","1510–1542":"1510–1542","1510–Male":"1510–Kuollut","1480–1575":"1480–1575","4 Jan 1535":"4. tammikuuta 1535","2 October 1542":"2. lokakuuta 1542","1580":"1580","1480":"1480","1491":"1491","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1535":"1535","1510":"1510","1575":"1575","1542":"1542","9 April 1575":"9. huhtikuuta 1575","about 1510":"noin 1510","1549":"1549","Yorkshire, England":"Yorkshire, England","England":"England","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England":"Shrewsbury, Shropshire, England","Muckleton, Shropshire, England":"Shropshire,